title.narrative: Improving the Capacity of Philippines Law Enforcement, Social Services, and Judiciary in Combating Human Trafficking

description.narrative: Between September 30, 2012 and September 30, 2014, the International Justice Mission (IJM) will continue its anti-sex trafficking work in Metro Manila. IJM's collaborative casework approach has allowed it to diagnose and address specific problems within the Philippines public justice system (PJS) that hamper an effective anti-trafficking response. Through capacity building trainings and targeted advocacy efforts, IJM has primarily sought to address these issues at the local level in partnership with anti-trafficking stakeholders and government partners. IJM will advocate with national government leaders and institutions for robust anti-trafficking police training and trauma-focused counseling programs to be implemented at government-run shelters and the creation and support for specialized anti-trafficking police units and safe, victim-friendly centers for processing and interviewing victims post-rescue. With national level mandates in hand, IJM will work with regional units within Metro-Manila to implement these protocols as well as build the capacity of the local government and community based organizations to establish reintegration centers. These structural changes will support an effective, independent PJS response to anti-trafficking in Metro Manila and will contribute to similar developments throughout the Philippines.
